      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Safety Calculus</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Leon Sirulnick letter disputes Robert A Levy's Sept 8 Op-Ed article, which argued against imposing additional restraints on tire industry</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Safety Can Cost Too Much,'' by Robert A. Levy (Op-Ed, Sept. 8):</p>
        <p>Mr. Levy uses the example of 40,000 automobile deaths a year without any resultant government safety regulations to support his claim that we should think twice about any additional restraints on the tire industry lest we price it out of existence.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Safety Can Cost Too Much,'' by Robert A. Levy (Op-Ed, Sept. 8):</p>
        <p>Mr. Levy uses the example of 40,000 automobile deaths a year without any resultant government safety regulations to support his claim that we should think twice about any additional restraints on the tire industry lest we price it out of existence.</p>
        <p>The problem with this example is that most automobile deaths are accidental. The Firestone fiasco is a result of either a design or a manufacturing flaw that went unreported for too many years.</p>
        <p>It was the lack of government oversight exemplified by the Republican policy of allowing industries  to be self-regulating that permitted an atmosphere of corporate obfuscation that brought us to this current situation.</p>
        <p>LEON SIRULNICK  Manalapan, N.J., Sept. 9, 2000</p>
      </block>
